I was having a problem when loading multiple fonts in the same scene where seemingly random fonts would not load. I tracked it down to this method in Font.cs:

```
public static FontFamily LoadFontFamilyFromMemory(byte[] memory)
{
    FontFamily result = null;
    GCHandle handle = GCHandle.Alloc(memory, GCHandleType.Pinned);
    try
    {
        IntPtr fontMemPtr = handle.AddrOfPinnedObject();
        fontManager.AddMemoryFont(fontMemPtr, memory.Length);
        result = fontManager.Families[fontManager.Families.Length - 1];
    }
    finally
    {
        handle.Free();
    }

    loadedFontRegistry[result.Name] = result;
    return result;
}
```

The method seems to make the assumption that a newly added font will be the last font in the list. On stepping through the code however I noticed that the fonts were being stored alphabetically. If you load a font beginning with D, followed by a font beginning with C, result actually gets assigned the font beginning with D because it is the last item in the list and so the font beginning with C is never added to the loadedFontRegistry. 
I took a stab at fixing it myself but too much of the surrounding code works on the same assumption and I'm not familiar enough with the context this exists in well enough to understand the side effects of the changes I would have had to make.

Potentially important context to this is that I am loading two fonts that have been serialised as resources on another machine. The original fonts are not installed on this machine and the fonts do not have links to a ttf in the media folder to fall back on so that are being loaded from the serialised customFamilyData.

